summary: This is an FBI incident report summarizing a complaint call received on April 14, 2020, regarding the Epstein case. The caller made multiple attempts to report crimes allegedly occurring at Jeffrey Epstein's Zorro Ranch, including rape, sex trafficking, blackmail using STDs, and a claim of a baby sacrifice. The caller was interviewed but provided limited information, refusing to name new victims and requesting information from the FBI about the case.

events.title: Complaint Calls to FBI
events.description: An individual called the Albuquerque FBI Operations Center approximately 5 times in one hour to report crimes related to the Epstein case. He was transferred to NTOC but claimed they would not take his report.

events.title: FBI Duty Agent Follow-up Call
events.description: Las Cruces Duty Agent called the complainant back using the provided phone number. The complainant did not provide clear information regarding his complaint.

events.title: Telephone Interview of Complainant
events.description: The complainant was interviewed via telephone. He made allegations about activities at Epstein's Zorro Ranch, including rape, sex trafficking, blackmail using STDs, and a baby sacrifice. He refused to name new victims.

events.title: Incident Report Transfer
events.description: The incident report was transferred and assigned to the NY-C20 squad following a discussion with SA MI.

locations: Zorro Ranch (Jeffrey Epstein's property in New Mexico)
Christ United Methodist Church (near Albuquerque, New Mexico)
keyFacts: A complainant made multiple calls to the FBI in April 2020 alleging that Jeffrey Epstein's Zorro Ranch was used for sex, rape, and giving victims STDs which were then used for blackmail.
The caller made a highly specific and extreme claim that a female victim was raped, became pregnant, and the baby was sacrificed and buried at the Christ United Methodist Church near Albuquerque.

The caller refused to provide names of new victims, only identifying Virginia Giuffre and Ghislaine Maxwell because their names were already public, and stated these individuals had previously contacted law enforcement to no avail.
The FBI report indicates the complainant was uncooperative in providing further details but repeatedly requested information from the FBI about the Epstein investigation.
The incident was ultimately transferred to the FBI's New York field office, specifically the NY-C20 squad, for handling.
